result.execSummary:
The defendant Duane Lashon Madge Jr. was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Duane Lashon Madge Jr. is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Duane Lashon Madge Jr. was found guilty of OWI (5th or 6th), a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).
  • Duane Lashon Madge Jr. was found guilty of Ignition Interlock Device Tampering/Failure to Install/Violate Court Order, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 347.413(1).
  • Duane Lashon Madge Jr. was found guilty of Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

records.addlTxt: Defendant Duane Lashon Madge Jr. in court.  Attorney Steven G. Richards in court for Duane Lashon Madge Jr.  Attorney Anthony Joseph Pozorski Sr. in court for State of Wisconsin. Per agreement, defendant will plead to Cts 1, 3, and 5 and State moves to dismiss Cts 2, 4, and 6. State will recommend the following: Ct 1: 4 years WSPS (2in and 2 out), $1000 fine plus cost, max DL revocation, and alcohol assessment; Ct 3: 30 days jail; Ct 5: 6 months jail. All periods of incarceration are concurrent to each other but consecutive to 22CF51. Court reviews plea questionnaire and finds defendant freely and knowingly waives rights. Defendant pleads no contest. Court accepts plea and finds defendant guilty. Cts 2, 4, and 6 are dismissed per agreement. State heard. Attorney Richards heard. Defendant heard. Court heard and orders the following: As to Ct. 1, 5 years WSPS (18months in and 42months out): Ct 3: 30 days; Ct 5: 6 months. All periods of incarceration are concurrent to each other but consecutive to 22CF51. Conditions of extended supervision are: if accepted, comply and satisfactory complete OWI or drug court program, not to possess or consume any alcohol, not to possess or consume any controlled substances unless prescribed and to be taken only as prescribed, to submit to random, observed testing of alcohol and controlled substances upon request of law enforcement, DOC, or designee, $150 fine plus costs for Ct 3, costs are waived on all other counts, and to submit a DNA sample. Defendant is eligible for challenge and substance abuse programming.
